    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <ab> 
                    <lb n="1"/> <gap reason="lost" quantity="3" unit="character" precision="low"/><supplied reason="lost">ḥ</supplied>bl 
                    <lb n="2"/> <gap reason="lost" quantity="4" unit="character" precision="low"/> a 
                    <lb n="3"/> <gap reason="lost" quantity="4" unit="character" precision="low"/> ṣḥl<unclear>m</unclear> a 
                    <lb n="4"/> <gap reason="lost" quantity="4" unit="character" precision="low"/> <gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/> </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>The only word that can be reconstructed is [ḥ]bl, translated as “Alas.”</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>ḥbl was a common lamentation in Palmyrene funerary sculpture, and thus we can supply
                    the necessary ḥ to produce ḥḇ(ā)l. The remaining three lines are fragmentary and
                    impossible to translate; however, the most likely option is the name of the
                    deceased and their ancestry. Line 3 suggests this is plausible for this case as
                    well: ṣḥlm is a common root for many words, but particularly for names. . In
                    line 3, I have chosen to read the third letter as a m because the down stroke at
                    the left is just about visible: the other option is to read it as an additional
                    lamedh which, if construed with the preceding two letters makes little sense.
                    However, it could go with the following a, which is not an uncommon
                    formulation.</p></div>
            

